<br>
If you actually go play a level 1 cleric and a level 1 wizard you'll discover that most battles are fought toe to toe with a mob.  In this situation, cast time makes a rather large difference in even being able to cast at all.<br>
<br>
I've played both, and with a wizard I can kill a mob using only nukes. Sometimes, I can even do it without getting hit if I kite.  With a cleric, I can open the fight with a nuke, and if I try nuking again I will most likely be interrupted.  Sometimes, on undead, I can fear them and nuke when they come in range, which winds up using up all my mana.<br>
<br>
Whatever the ratios and max nuke values are... irrelevant.  Whoever tuned those spells knew exactly what they were doing for a level one character.  When you play a level 1 wiz, you nuke stuff.  When you play a level one cleric, you melee mostly, and maybe use a nuke here or there when you get the opportunity, or heal if you must. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugrimstafftheurgist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimstaff Theurgist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 5176<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/5/02 9:17 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Nuking....what really should have happend</span><hr size=1> Your quote does nothing to resolve the problem of diverging power I laid out, I don't even understand what you are trying to prove by it.  You can NEVER have enough defense, because the way the game is laid out defense will never be absolute (it never keeps you immune to damage), nor damage absolute (kills anything without you suffering).<br>
<br>
&quot;I've played both, and with a wizard I can kill a mob using only nukes. Sometimes, I can even do it without getting hit if I kite. With a cleric, I can open the fight with a nuke, and if I try nuking again I will most likely be interrupted. Sometimes, on undead, I can fear them and nuke when they come in range, which winds up using up all my mana.&quot;<br>
<br>
Let me remind you of what it was like to play a Cleric at low levels, since either you've forgotten or you didn't nuke much and are making assumptions.   I suggest you go actually make a Cleric and Wizard in the same zone and kill a few creatures using nukes, to refresh your memory - because I've done that very thing a few times in the past.<br>
<br>
You are assuming here that<br>
A) the Cleric's spells cast so slowly they'll be interrupted<br>
B) the only way to use nukes is to run about away from a monster an hit them at range.<br>
<br>
For Point A I refer you to the fact that the Cleric's casting time is only .4 (less than half) second difference, and Frost Bolt is actually longer at level 1.  I have successfully and quite often kept casting cleric blasts while being hit, in fact its sometimes easier than with a Wizard because THE CLERICS AC CAN BE MORE THAN DOUBLE A WIZARDS.<br>
<br>
Further, you can sit and fight a monster up close using only blasts, you'll do reasonably well as a Wizard, and just as well as a Cleric - better if you factor in that a Cleric can not only heal themself, but can use a better weapon and can melee better when they are oom.<br>
<br>
But all of this is academic and has nothing to do with the entire discussion.  If Wizards had a blast that was 2 points higher but slower than a Cleric you'd be trying to argue &quot;Wizards are more powerful!!!!  See, it does more!&quot;  The point everyone is trying to make here is that Clerics do TOO MUCH DAMAGE.  Is that clear to you yet?  TOO MUCH DAMAGE, you know as well as I do that mana ratios and damage done are not &quot;irrelevant&quot; despite how dismissing this information helps your attempt.<br>
<br>
You further assume that the designers knew exactly what they were doing when they did the low level characters and I disagree most strongly to this.  I don't believe they were paying that close attention to what they were doing with damage numbers, they reduced Wizard numbers without proper attention to the other classes' damage overall, and we ended up with stupid stuff like level 34-38 with Mages.  However, even if they DID do this carefully, you are assuming that since most clerics don't nuke (some are totally unaware they get nukes) that this somehow justifies in any sense what was done.  It doesn't, the fact that Clerics don't USE this advantage makes no difference whatsoever, Wizards had a strong advantage (thought not clear enough some levels) in AE for a long time before people like Myztic and I were able to get it through to people's heads it wasn't suicide.  Was that advantage not there? <p><IMG SRC="http://www.kestrelarts.com/images/book.jpg" ></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usiryakk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sir Yakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 34<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/7/02 1:58 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> And Goladus, take away nukes and Clerics are virtually unchanged. The fact that you can come up with some odd situation where Clerics will nuke because they have little else do to does NOT change this fact. Clerics hardly ever nuke, they wouldn't miss nukes if they were taken away ENTIRELY except in very very tiny portions of the game. That's &quot;virutally unchanged&quot; regardless of how you want to argue.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
